5lt.title: Antisymmetric relation
5lt.clickbait: A binary relation where no two distinct elements are related in both directions
5lt.text:
An antisymmetric relation is a relation where no two distinct elements are related in both directions. In other words. $R$ is antisymmetric iff

$(aRb ∧ bRa) → a = b$

and consequently, $a ≠ b → ¬(aRb ∧ bRa)$

Antisymmetry is *not* the negation of [symmetric_relation Symmetry]. Due to the fact that $aRa$ is allowed in an antisymmetric relation, the equivalence relation, $\{(0,0), (1,1), (2,2)...\}$ is both symmetric and antisymmetric.

Examples also include the successor relation ($\{(0,1), (1,2), (2,3), (3,4)...\}$), or a relation linking numbers to their prime factors ($\{...(9,3),(10,5),(10,2),(14,7),(14,2)...)\}$)
